column1: How many seats in Taiwan's Legislative Yuan will the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) win in January's elections?
column6: ['Non-US Politics']
column11: The Democratic Progressive Party could potentially win control of the both the presidency and the Legislative Yuan after January's general elections. This has broad implications for Taiwan's relationship with China and the United States' foreign policies in Asia (The World in 2016, Brookings, Global Risk Insights). The election is scheduled for 16 January 2016.

To answer this question, I first started researching about Taiwan. Although I had heard of the Sunflower Movement and studied the history of China and Taiwan, I had not at all followed any of the political events in any level of detail. Currently the two leading parties in Taiwan are the KMT and DPP. The major political issues are the relationship with China and the economy (which are obviously two very interlinked issues). The two main and opposing views with respect to both these issues, is whether Mainland China and Taiwan should be unified into one country, or if Taiwan is and forever will be a separate nation. The DPP and its affiliated parties, known as the Pan-Green coalition, assert that Taiwan is a separate country from the PRC. The KMT and its affiliated parties, known as the Pan-Blue coalition, assert the opposite and have as their aim either a closer relationship with China or in some cases even a total unification of the PRC and Taiwan. The KMT have dominated politics since 1947, with the DPP having some control on and off in the last ten years. As of 2009, the KMT led government has been rapidly improving the political and economic relationship with China, and China is now one of the closest trading partners of Taiwan. It should be noted that both the KMT and DPP leadership have in the past been accused of corruption on several different occasions. There are other political parties in Taiwan, however they are minority parties that are already closely aligned with either the DPP or KMT. This alignment is mainly related to the discussion of whether Taiwan should be an independent nation, or whether Taiwan and mainland China should reunite.

In the next election there will be more younger voters who increasingly view themselves as Taiwanese and thus distinct from China. In turn associating themselves more with the DDP then the current majority.
http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1899633/taiwan-candidates-get-theatrical-packed-final-leg-presidential-election

It's been a good year for insurgents, malcontents, and oppositions in general. The DPP are on track to follow the trend. The KMT's One Big Idea--"Let's be buddies with Big China"--seems to have run out of whatever steam it ever had. The recent relative weakness of the PRC economy has likely contributed to this.
As of today, I cannot find much of substance to counter the prospect of a DPP majority.

I don't imagine that the DPP will have an enormous majority on their own as, despite the fact that the FPTP system should work in their favour this time, a significant number of the undecideds are likely to vote KMT - not least as turnout could be high at around 77-82% and an older, conservative population will make up a large proportion of these voters. The DPP will probably win approximately as many seats as the KMT's previous tally of 64 seats - somewhere between 62-68 seats, perhaps. However, with the likely success of the NPP (maybe winning up to 5-7 seats?), the DPP should be able to form quite a strong Pan-Green coalition.
DPP will fall just short of the necessary 57 seats for a majority.

The FPTP system lends itself to majorities, which has been Taiwan's general history in legislative elections (12 of 14 - 86%), though admittedly much of this was within a Kuomintang-only paradigm. Times are different now, with two of the last four elections been pluralities. From a base rate perspective this suggests somewhere between 50-85%, say 65%. The analysis by Jean-Pierre seems to suggest a majority is possible and the DPP are leading in the polls quite well (though there is a reasonably high level of non-respondents), so assuming the non-respondents distribute in line with polling they would get about 40% of the vote, which seems to sit exactly in the middle of the threshold between plurality (<35%) or majority (>45%). The DPP also seem to be dipping in the polls a little, so on balance I'm going to stick with the 65%
credit to Jean-Pierre

Here is a somewhat cautious projection of the number of seats the DPP will win, with total seats for each city/county in parentheses. In some cases, I have listed the particular seats the DPP should win after the # sign. 57 seats is required for an absolute majority.

DPP is leading in the polls, it seems highly unlikely their big lead will be reversed. Say 5%. Remains 95 to be divided between plurality or majority. DPP needs 57 seats. I guess based on December polls DPP can expect over 40% of the votes or ~14-15 seats for the proportional representation part of the yuan. Assuming the Aborigine seats are a loss the DPP needs another 42 or 43 seats of the 73 districts with a First past the post method. I can't find any polls per seat. The KMT got 48 district seats with 45% of the votes in 2012. Seems that should be enough to make if the current polls are accurate and nothing changes.
http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-35192142

The DPP has been consistently gained the most support in polls from the end of 2015 to now. Interestingly, the DPP's results in legislative polls lags behind that of its Presidential candidate. That suggests they will get the most votes. Taiwan's parliament has 113 seats. 73 are elected in geographical districts and 34 based on proportion of the national vote. First, based on national polls, it seems likely the DPP's floor is about 40% (that gets them 14 of 34 proportional seats). To get to a majority, the DPP would need win 43 of the 73 constituencies (almost 60%). Unless undecided voters break dramatically against the DPP, because of the first past the post system Taiwan uses, it seems the most probably outcome would be a DPP majority.
Stating on majority,but even with the Polls, could still end up with a plurality. I think it will be close in either instance

Recent polls put the DPP at around 35% in the single member districts and 30% in the proportional representation seats. The PR seats will likely translate more directly to seats, so we can take this as roughly 30% of the 34 PR seats (or around 10 seats there). In the single member districts (first-past-the-post system) a polling of around 35% should translate into a more significant share of these seats given that the DPP will likely be the largest party in many of these districts. It is conceivable that this type of polling would result in around 60-70% share in the 73 seats elected with this method (or around 45-50 seats). This would suggest that a majority is quite possible, but that plurality is very close behind.

I'm giving even odds for a DPP plurality (38%) and KMT majority/plurality (38%) mainly because a big victory for Tsai in the presidential elections may not translate into equally big victories her party in the Legislative Yuan (LY) election. The KMT has a structural advantage in the latter that may help it keep a majority even as it loses the presidency by wide margins. The DPP would certainly pick up extra seats among those allocated proportionally, but the majority of seats are winner-take-all. I'll need to do a district-by-district analysis of those seats at some later date once the slate of candidates and maybe some polls for individual LY races are available.
